name: Nancy Pelosi
content:
Today, our nation marks 58 years of the Equal Pay Act, which enshrined ‚Äòequal pay for equal work‚Äô into law. This vital principle is foundational to our democracy‚Äôs promise of full equality and imperative for our nation‚Äôs economic success. While we have made some progress over the last six decades, equal pay is not yet a reality: women are still paid only 82 cents for every dollar paid to men. For women of color, the gap is far worse: Black women make 63 cents, Native women make 60 cents and Latinas make 55 cents.

As we commemorate this anniversary, our nation is recovering from a pandemic that has taken an unjust, uneven toll on women. Last year, 4.5 million women ‚Äì and disproportionately women of color ‚Äì lost or were forced to leave their jobs during the pandemic. Economists estimate that it could take nearly two years for women‚Äôs employment to return to pre-pandemic levels. It is both a moral and an economic imperative that, as we Build Back Better, we unleash the full power of women in the workforce ‚Äì because when women succeed, America succeeds.

That is why Democrats are fighting hard to enact the Paycheck Fairness Act, which would strengthen the Equal Pay Act by finally providing effective remedies for women who are not receiving equal pay for equal work. Although Republicans in the Senate are blocking this vital, bipartisan and overwhelmingly popular bill, we will not relent until we secure the wages that working women deserve. In addition, President Biden and the Democratic Congress are hard at work advancing the American Jobs and Families Plans, which will help women return to the workforce by expanding access to child care, health care, workplace safety and more. Today, and every day, let us recommit to lifting up working women and finishing the work the Equal Pay Act began.

name: Ralph Norman
content:
If you‚Äôre scratching your head over this, join the crowd. Shortly after killing a pipeline that would have helped Americans and U.S. energy independence, Biden goes on to remove the only legal barriers we have opposing another pipeline that will promote RUSSIAN dominance and likely make our European allies more reliant on Vladimir Putin.

Whose side is he on?!

Here‚Äôs the background information: Shortly after taking office, President Biden revoked the permits for the Keystone XL pipeline, which would have helped efficiently transport crude oil from Canada to our own refineries here in the United States. Yesterday, the company behind the pipeline finally terminated the project, and formally walked away from this endeavor.

That was climate activism on the part of Biden. There‚Äôs no other way to explain it.

Like it or not, we need fossil fuels until cleaner alternatives can fully supply the energy our nation needs to survive and prosper. That crude oil is going to be refined, one way or another. If it‚Äôs not here, then it‚Äôll be in another country. So when our President deliberately obstructs things like the Keystone XL pipeline, it just increases our reliance on foreign nations for the energy we need, and makes the cost of fuels higher for all of us in the long run.

Meanwhile on a related front, Biden went on to actually LIFT sanctions on the Nord Stream 2 pipeline. That‚Äôs a natural gas line being built under the Baltic Sea between Russia and Germany. We placed sanctions on it, in part, because this pipeline will make our allies in Europe heavily reliant on Russian energy at a time when Vladimir Putin is causing problems throughout the world.

So to recap Biden‚Äôs actions here: (1) A pipeline that helps America? Bad; shut it down. (2) A pipeline that helps Russia? It‚Äôs fine; carry on.

name: Christopher A. Coons
content:
If you slept in late this AM, NASA has you covered! Absolutely stunning views from Cape Henlopen and the National Mall in D.C.

NASA Sun Science
21 hrs ¬∑

Did you see today‚Äôs solar eclipse? Show us your photos!

People in parts of the Northern Hemisphere saw a partial or annular solar eclipse today. üåô These photos of the partial solar eclipse are from our NASA photographers on the East Coast. See more of their photos here: https://www.flickr.com/photos/nasahqphoto/albums/72157719391182014/

Solar eclipses happen when the Sun, Moon, and Earth line up in the same plane, allowing the Moon to cast its shadow on Earth. During an annular eclipse, the Moon is near its farthest point from Earth in its orbit, so it appears too small in the sky to ever completely cover the Sun. As the Moon passes in front of the Sun, it leaves a ‚Äòring of fire‚Äô around its edges for observers in the path of annularity. People outside this path may see a partial solar eclipse ‚Äî that‚Äôs what was visible in parts of the US this morning right around sunrise.

name: James M. Inhofe
content:
President Biden gave us a budget that cuts defense spending when we need real growth. His administration want the military to do more on climate change and pandemic response, among plenty of other things. More mission‚Äîbut with fewer resources.

The Chinese defense budget has grown 450 percent since 2001. They added $200 billion in the last decade while we cut $400 billion‚Äîand that‚Äôs just the investment we know about. As a result, we‚Äôre behind in some areas and falling behind in others.

So I‚Äôm worried deterrence will fail: maybe today, or in five or ten years. And when it does, the cost will be much higher than any investment we could make today to prevent it. This budget isn‚Äôt making hard choices. It‚Äôs making bad and short-sighted choices.

Today, the Senate Armed Services Committee heard from Secretary of Defense Lloyd Austin; General Mark Milley, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff; and Michael McCord, DOD Comptroller, where they discussed the FY22 budget. Congress has a lot of work to do to right-size defense spending.

name: Bruce Westerman
content:
America‚Äôs precious federal lands and national parks should be available to everyone, regardless of age or physical ability. I offered an amendment in last night‚Äôs Transportation and Infrastructure Committee markup to ensure seniors and people with disabilities are able to use off-highway vehicles to access our federal lands and national parks on roads already open to vehicle traffic. Every Democrat voted against it. Public lands are not a privilege for only the young and able-bodied, but an experience for every American to enjoy.

Not every American can hike for miles into the backcountry of a national forest or national park. Seniors and those with disabilities often need the assistance of a motorized, off-highway vehicle. Responsible use of these vehicles should be encouraged by the Federal Government so Americans of all ages and abilities can enjoy the public lands supported by their tax dollars. My amendment would have guaranteed that ability.

Every Arkansan should be able to enjoy the splendor of the Ouachita and Ozark National Forests and Hot Springs National Park. By rejecting my amendment, Democrats made it more difficult for seniors and the disabled to do so. This is not right. America‚Äôs public lands should be open and accessible to everyone.

name: Alan S. Lowenthal
content:
On Tuesday, I joined the Natural Resources Water Oceans and Wildlife subcommittee hearing on the dumping of potentially hundreds of thousands barrels of DDT and chemical waste in federal waters between Long Beach and Catalina Island from the 1930s-1970s. A recent Scripps Institution of Oceanography survey of the dump sites proves what we have long suspected, that the dumping of DDT and other toxic substances off the coast of Los Angeles was more pervasive than we had known. It also makes clear that despite decades of claims by the industries involved, the dumping was done outside of the then-approved areas and closer to shore and population centers than was allowed. Despite the dumping stopping decades ago, DDT continue to show up in marine wildlife in the area. I look forward to continuing to work with California Senator Feinstein and my colleagues in the House to get more information about this dumping and pushing for important next steps to deal with this toxic legacy. I also want to thank Avalon Assistant City Manager Michael Parmer for his testimony at the hearing highlighting the potential impacts to Avalon and Catalina Island by this dumping and for his dedication to the safety of the Catalina Island community.

https://www.courthousenews.com/lawmakers-warned-of-potential-widespread-effects-of-ddt-dump-site/

COURTHOUSENEWS.COM

Dr. Li Wenliang heroically tried to warn Chinese citizens about COVID-19, only to be silenced by the authoritarian Chinese Communist Party until his tragic death. This project was slowed during the Trump Presidency, but the Biden Administration gave a gift to Putin and will aid in his efforts to increase his stranglehold over Europe. Under the Trump Administration, and through innovation in the private sector, the United States is the number one oil and gas producer globally.

But don't forget, as one of his very first acts earlier this year, President Biden revoked the permit for the Keystone XL pipeline, which was critical to our energy security and a top priority to our Canadian allies. And just yesterday, the Keystone XL project was officially canceled. It is truly baffling and illogical that President Biden is willing to green-light Russian energy projects over American energy projects and jobs. Projects like the Keystone XL pipeline and the Atlantic Coast Pipeline would have continued the US trend in leading the world in carbon emission reduction.

For the entirety of the Trump Administration, Democrats were obsessed with imagined Russian influence over Trump policies and repeatedly called him a Russian agent. If Trump had waived sanctions on a Russian company, friends of Putin, like the Biden Administration just did, there would be an immediate call for an investigation - and maybe even impeachment.

President Biden has talked tough about holding Putin accountable, but his actions have been the exact opposite.

name: Lisa Murkowski
content: I recently visited Ekuk, a community in the Bristol Bay region with only three year-round residents. The town is quiet in the winter months, but completely comes alive each summer during fishing season. While in town, I had a tour of Ekuk Fisheries, the local salmon processing plant. I appreciated seeing the facility and learning more about the how the community functions. All of the fish harvested in Ekuk are by set-net fishermen and then delivered fresh to the processing facility. Many of the families who fish in Ekuk have been doing so for generations. My visit was a good reminder not only of all the hard work that goes into getting salmon from the ocean to the dinner table, but also the long-standing history that helped make Bristol Bay the world renowned fishing community that it is today.

name: Don Young
content:
This month‚Äôs state work period has been very busy! I recently visited the Fisher House facilities on JBER alongside Lieutenant General David Krumm, Commander of the Alaskan Command.

Our recovering heroes deserve to have their loved ones by their sides, but not every family can afford the immense expenses of the lodging arrangements required to be with one another. The Fisher House Foundation has been instrumental in funding temporary lodging near medical facilities so that the families of servicemembers can be with those they are helping to care for.

I have been a long-time supporter of the Fisher House Foundation and its mission. Last Congress, alongside my dear friend, Congresswoman Debbie Dingell (D-MI), I secured an additional $5 million in funding for the Fisher House Foundation, doubling their total to $10 million. In Congress, I will continue standing up for these dedicated advocates and caretakers.

I am very grateful for everything the staff at JBER‚Äôs Fisher House has accomplished for our servicemembers and their families. I want to thank House Manager Theresa Nedrow, Lt Gen David Krumm, and all the staff for hosting me for a very productive visit. May God Bless our military!

name: Doug Lamborn
content:
Yesterday, I was joined by the Bremer family on a tour of the Ronald McDonald House In Colorado Springs. The Ronald McDonald House Charities of Southern Colorado helps provide respite and comfort to families with critically ill children so that they may remain close to each other during a child's time in care. Along with their many public-private partnerships in our community, they provide resources such as transportation, hot meals, comfortable space to rest, and everything a parent or family member would need so that their focus can remain on their sick child. Eli Bremer, Cami Bremer, and 5 year old Struthers, shared their story about how the Ronald McDonald House supported their family when Struthers was born premature and needed long-term neonatal care. The "House that Love Built" is genuinely a home full of comfort, art, community, and hope.

Special thanks to Beth Alessio, Sara Correll, Steve Bigari, Moyra Hower, and the fantastic staff and volunteers at the RMHCSC in Colorado Springs. Your leadership and mission to serve families in our community during a challenging time are critical to the health and well-being of the Pikes Peak region.

I just finished a 19-hour markup of the INVEST Act, a strong piece of legislation that will rebuild our crumbling roads, bridges, rail systems, and more with American materials and workers to withstand the impacts of climate change and boost the American economy.

I am pleased to share the Oregon Department of Transportation I-5 Aurora-Donald Interchange Improvement Project is a step closer to becoming a reality. name: Daniel Webster
content:
Since taking office, President Biden and Democrats in Congress have taken government spending ‚Äì which was already too high - to unprecedented levels.

I ran for office pledging to do my part to stop the spigot of spending. I've supported and introduced legislation that prioritized and reduced spending. I am confident we can set our nation on a responsible fiscal path while still investing in critical priorities including more border security, infrastructure projects and our military. It starts with the House and Senate rejecting the practice of last-minute funding deals that are negotiated behind closed doors by a small group of lawmakers.

content:
I am very pleased that critical funding and priorities I submitted on behalf of my constituents, commuters, and transit agencies are included in this bill. I thank all of our cities and local stakeholders for their valued input, which will help bring federal dollars to our region to put people back to work, while ensuring our long-term infrastructure needs are addressed. As the senior Californian on the Committee, I am proud that this bill will provide $38 billion in transportation funding for California, including $27 billion for highway projects and $11 billion for transit. The INVEST in America Act will make a significant impact in improving American lives by reducing commute times, increasing safety on our highways, bridges, buses and rails, and safeguarding our environment. name: Robin L. Kelly
content:
The Equal Pay Act was enacted 58 years ago, but the gender pay gap remains wide today ‚Äî even as more women are the main breadwinners for their families. According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics data, women earn 82 cents for every dollar a man earns, and the gap is even wider for women of color!

Two months ago in the House, we passed the Paycheck Fairness Act, which would strengthen the Equal Pay Act and help women achieve equal pay. But on Tuesday, the Senate refused to bring the bill up for a vote. Unless women make their voices heard, the bill will go nowhere. Women must let their senators know that 82 cents to a dollar is not enough and that they deserve the same pay as the guy sitting next to them. #EqualPayDay

POLITICO.COM

name: Randy K. Weber, Sr.
content:
üö® PLEASE CHECK YOUR PASSPORTS üö®

Before you make any travel plans, please remember to check the expiration date!

The Department of State is experiencing delays in receiving passport applications due to unprecedented mail volume and other COVID-19 impacts on both the U.S. Postal Service and local passport processing centers.

You can now apply for routine service and expect to receive a passport in 10-12 weeks*. You also have the option of paying an additional $60 for expedited service to receive your passport in 4-6 weeks.

These processing times apply to applications submitted by mail and in-person at an acceptance facility in your community. Most acceptance facilities such as post offices, clerks of court, and libraries are open and accepting passport applications.

The Department of State encourages you to apply by mail when possible because it is a safe, contactless option for certain services.

If you plan to expedite your passport application due to upcoming travel plans, we recommend that you send your application using USPS' Priority Mail Express.

All of the passport agencies and centers are processing passport applications. Because of increases in COVID-19 cases and changing local health conditions, agencies and centers offer extremely limited in-person services if you need to travel internationally in the next 72 hours (3 business days).

Should you have any issues regarding applying for or renewing a passport for an upcoming trip, don't forget, my office is here to help.

I'm here today at the West Milford Wetlands Environmental Center to announce federal action to 1) help combat Lyme disease and 2) protect North Jersey families from ticks and Lyme disease, as children and families enjoy outdoor activities this summer.

We need to ensure Lyme disease patients have the care and treatment they need, while also protecting our families from this tick-borne disease.

content:
As the cost of living rises and the shortage of affordable housing grows, community organizations are looking for creative ways to develop new affordable housing units near city centers or along accessible transit lines.

I'm glad to hear that the House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure just passed the INVEST in America Act including a bill I recently introduced. My bill, the Promoting Affordable Housing Near Transit Act, will help provide an opportunity for transit entities to partner with community-driven organizations and utilize unused land for affordable transit-accessible housing for the people who need it most.
